<p>The number of cells in the perimeter depends on the assumed number of neighbors per cell, 
 <italic>k</italic>, and the radius of infection, i.e., the expansion phase, 
 <italic>n</italic> (
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="viruses-10-00200-f003">Figure 3</xref>A). Initially, having only one infected cell, 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm52">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>f</mi>
      <mi>c</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <mn>1</mn>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> as the perimeter equals the whole focus size. After the first expansion phase, 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm53">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>n</mi>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <mn>1</mn>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>, the number of cells in the perimeter is equivalent to the total number of neighbors of a cell, i.e., 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm54">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>f</mi>
      <mi>c</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <mi>k</mi>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. After the second and third expansion phase, the number of cells in the perimeter doubles and triples, respectively, while the total focus size grows slightly faster (
 <xref ref-type="fig" rid="viruses-10-00200-f003">Figure 3</xref>A). In general, the proportion of cells in a focus contributing to cell-to-cell transmission (CC contributors) after completion of expansion phase 
 <italic>n</italic> and dependent on the assumed number of neighbors, 
 <italic>k</italic>, is determined by:
 <disp-formula id="FD7-viruses-10-00200">
  <label>(7)</label>
  <math id="mm55">
   <mrow>
    <mtable displaystyle="true">
     <mtr>
